@REM -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@REM                                                                                           |
@REM Englische Version:                                                                        |
@REM                                                                                           |
@REM -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

@node Over "Overview"
@prev "Main"
@next "Feat"

 @{b}@{u}Overview@{ub}@{uu}

AmiDynDNS is an Amiga client for @{i}DynDNS.org@{ui} DNS services.
It supports the actual NIC-2 protocol of DynDNS with update of
multiple hosts (see @{"Features" link Feat}).

Additional it's a @{i}CLI/GUI hybrid application@{ui}, so you can use it from
cli as good as from wb. (see @{"CLI or GUI" link CGUI})

There are several other clients available from Aminet, but as far
as i tested them, they don't support the current NIC-2 protocol of
DynDNS and so they won't work. Except an ARexx script and i don't
like scripts very much.. ;)

That's why i decide to write a new one. AmiDynDNS is not a port
of any other client. It's written from scratch, based on the
developer information distributed by DynDNS.org.

@endnode
@node Feat "Features"
@next "Requ"
@prev "Feat"

 @{b}@{u}Features@{ub}@{uu}

    o DynDNS NIC-2 compliant

    o CLI/GUI hybrid application

    o simple font sensitive GUI for Workbench use

    o updating of @{b}multiple@{ub} hosts of one account at the same time

    o Checks for invalid local IPs (10.x.x.x, 127.0.0.1, etc.)

    o Checks if hosts are already up to date and updates only those which
      aren't to avoid host-blocking 

    o optional @{b}logfile@{ub} with time, date, host, ip and status records

    o optional @{b}configfile@{ub} for short command lines and multiple
      accounts

    o optional web-based IP detection (LAN,...)

    o direct SMC Barricade Router (DSL) support for IP detection

    o no port but written from scratch in Ansi-C with respect to
      C= Commodore programming styleguide ;-)

    o more to come? (see @{"Future" link Futu})

@endnode
@node Requ "System Requirements"
@next "Inst"
@prev "Feat"

 @{b}@{u}System Requirements@{ub}@{uu}

To use AmiDynDNS you must have:

    o AmigaOS 3.x

    o some free mem
      (some KB should work ;) )

    o bsdsocket.library v4+
	  (as included in Roadshow, AmiTCP v4, Miami, MiamiDx, Genesis, etc.)

    o one or more DynDNS accounts
      (register freely at www.dyndns.org)

@{i}@{u}Note:@{ui}@{uu} @{b}In theory@{ub} it should work with OS2.x too, but this is @{b}not@{ub} tested!

@endnode
@node Inst "Installation"
@next "Usag"
@prev "Requ"

 @{b}@{u}Installation@{ub}@{uu}

    o Place the AmiDynDNS drawer wherever you want

For use @{i}without@{ui} configfile you're done ;-) See @{"Usage from CLI" link Usag} or
@{"Usage from WB" link UsWB} for instructions on how to use AmiDynDNS.

For use @{i}with@{ui} configfile, see @{"Configfile" link Conf} for details about path and
structure of the file and create one. After that start AmiDynDNS as
mentioned in @{"Usage" link Usag}.


@{b}IMPORTANT:@{ub} If you want to use AmiDynDNS from Workbench with its
              GUI, you @{b}MUST@{ub} setup a correct configfile!

Of course you can start AmiDynDNS from a script (AmiTCP), Miami event
or similiar to do the update automatically. For a description of how
to add programs to scripts or events please refer to the manual of
your TCP/IP stack.
@endnode

@node Usag "Usage from CLI"
@prev "Inst"
@next "UsWB"

 @{b}@{u}Usage from CLI@{ub}@{uu}

@{u}Usage with configfile@{uu}
(See down below for usage without configfile)

First create a configfile as mentioned in @{"Configfile" link Conf}
section. If already done so continue reading, if not, do it and come
back again ;)


@{"Create new Configfile" SYSTEM "ed AmiDynDNS.cfg"}


If you've created a correct configfile and copied it to the AmiDynDNS
or to your S: directory, all you must do additionally is to start
AmiDynDNS without @{b}user@{ub}, @{b}pass@{ub} and @{b}host@{ub} argument. Surely you can
use all other options (some may override the options given in config).
After calling AmiDynDNS it will first search for AmiDynDNS.cfg in its
programdir, if it doesn't find it, it starts a search in your S: dir.
Once the configfile were found AmiDynDNS will process any given hosts
of any given user.

e.g., your configfile looks like this:

----------------snip-------------------
@{b}#
# Sample configfile for AmiDynDNS
#

<account>
user=ben
pass=benspass
host=foo.dyndns.org
</account>

<account>
user=john
pass=johnspass
host=bar.dyndns.org
</account>@{ub}

----------------snip-------------------

And your call of AmiDynDNS is:

    5.Internet:AmiDynDNS1.19> @{b}AmiDynDNS quiet log webip@{ub}

AmiDynDNS tries to update the host 'foo.dyndns.org' of user 'ben' and
the host 'bar.dyndns.org' of user 'john' and writes the status of each
host in the logfile (S:AmiDynDNS.log), but gives no output on screen
and uses the web-based IP detection (e.g. for LAN).

Too easy, isn't it? ;)




@{u}@{b}Usage without configfile@{ub}@{uu}

Template for AmiDynDNS:

    @{b}USER/K,PASS/K,HOST/K/M,SYSTEM/K,WILD/S,MX/K,BACKMX/S,PROXY/S,OFFLINE/S,
	WEBIP/S,QUIET/S,LOG/S,LOGPATH/K,CONFPATH/K,FORCE/S,SETENVIP/S,HELP/S@{ub}

Options in detail:

@{b}USER@{ub}        This @{i}keyword@{ui} must be followed by your DynDNS user ID.

@{b}PASS@{ub}        This @{i}keyword@{ui} must be followed by your DynDNS password.

@{b}HOST@{ub}        This @{i}keyword@{ui} must be followed by one or more of your hosts
            you want to update. Two or more hosts must be seperated by
            whitspace ' '.

@{b}SYSTEM@{ub}      This @{i}keyword@{ui} must be followed by the DNS system you wish to
            use at DynDNS.'DYNDNS' will update a dynamic host, 'STATDNS'
            will update a static host, while 'CUSTOM' will update a
            MyDynDNS Custom DNS host.
            Defaul: DYNDNS
            Overrides the configfile option!

@{b}WILD@{ub}        This @{i}switch@{ui} activates the wildcard option for your host(s)
            on DynDNS. If active, your DynDNS hosts are also reachable by
            any subdomain. E.g, your host is foo.dyndns.org, bar.foo.dyndns.org
            or fubar.foo.dyndns.org or any other subdomain will point to
            the same IP as foo.dyndns.org itself.
            Overrides the configfile option!

@{b}MX@{ub}          This @{i}keyword@{ui} must be followed by a full qualified domain name
            or valid IP address of your Mail eXchanger. That's a host where
            all mails for your DynDNS host will delivered to.
            Overrides the configfile option!

@{b}BACKMX@{ub}      This @{i}switch@{ui} makes only sense in conjunction with a valid MX host
            given. It sets up the given MX host as a backup. This means that
            mail will first attempt to deliver to your host directly, and
            will be delivered to the MX listed as a backup.
            Overrides the configfile option!

@{b}PROXY@{ub}       This @{i}switch@{ui} will cause  AmiDynDNS to use Port 8245 instead
            of Port 80 to bypass proxy servers.

@{b}OFFLINE@{ub}     This @{i}switch@{ui} sets the given hosts to offline, if specified.
            Note that this affects @{i}only@{ui} donator accounts! On all
            other accounts this won't take any effect except an error
            message of DynDNS.

@{b}WEBIP@{ub}       This @{i}switch@{ui} activates the web-based IP detection. This is
            useful, if you are behind a gateway or router and your computer
            only owns a private IP (10.x.x.x, 192.168.x.x, ...). Should
            only used if normal IP detection fails!

@{b}QUIET@{ub}       This @{i}switch@{ui} deactivates all output normally generated
            by AmiDynDNS. Note that you will get *NO* status information
            about your updates, but if a system error occur (e.g. file not
            found, library fails, etc.), it will be printed on screen. For
            status information the LOG switch may probably help.

@{b}LOG@{ub}         This @{i}switch@{ui} activates the logging function of AmiDynDNS.
            If specified a logfile will be generated in your S: directory
            called AmiDynDNS.log.
            It will be created if it doesn't exist and it will never get
            greater than 4 KB. If this size is reached, a backup is made
            (Also in your S: directory called AmiDynDNS.log.bak) and a new
            AmiDynDNS.log is created. Note that a backup will only be created
            if the filesize is greater than 4 KB and if the date of the last
            logged entry is older than the actual date, because all entries
            of one day should be together in one file for better reading.
            There will never be more than this two files.

@{b}FORCE@{ub}       This @{i}switch@{ui} forces AmiDynDNS to update the hosts even if the
            hosts are up to date already or a local IP is given.
            @{b}Please use with care, because of DynDNS is blocking hosts which
            are updated to often and local IPs aren't really good in the INet!@{ub}

@{b}LOGPATH@{ub}     This @{i}keyword@{ui} could be followed by a path which ADD will use to
            save the logfile there (if logging is enabled with LOG).
            Default: S:

@{b}CONFPATH@{ub}    This @{i}keyword@{ui} could be followed by a path where ADD will search its
            configfile 'AmiDynDNS.cfg'. If it can't find it there, the progdir
            and S: is searched for.
            Default: 'progdir' and S:

@{b}SETENVIP@{ub}    This @{i}switch@{ui} causes AmiDynDNS to write the actual IP address
            in the enviroment variable 'IP' (Env:IP). This might be useful
            if the host is behind a router and for example if you want to use
            RC-FTPd in passive-mode.

@{b}HELP@{ub}        This @{i}switch@{ui} displays a little helptext.



@{u}Examples@{uu}:

1.)

To update the host "foo.dyndns.org" of user "foo" with password
"bar":

    5.Internet:AmiDynDNS1.19> @{b}AmiDynDNS user=foo pass=bar host=foo.dyndns.org@{ub}

2.)

To update the hosts "foo.dyndns.org" and "bar.dnsalias.net" of
user "foo" with password "bar" with logging enabled:

    5.Internet:AmiDynDNS1.19> @{b}AmiDynDNS user foo pass bar host foo.dyndns.org bar.dnsalias.net log@{ub}

(As you can see the equals '=' between keyword and argument are not
necessary)

3.)

For automatic update without output add a command line to your TCP/IP
stack (startnet of AmiTCP, online event of Miami, etc.) like this:

    5.Internet:AmiDynDNS1.19> @{b}AmiDynDNS user=foo pass=bar host=foo.dyndns.org host2 [...] quiet log@{ub}

For [...] you could give AmiDynDNS even more of your hosts to
update.
@endnode


@node UsWB "Usage from Workbench"
@next "Conf"
@prev "Usag"

 @{b}@{u}Usage from Workbench@{ub}@{uu}



Note: To use ADD over its gui, you @{b}must@{ub} create a correct configuration
      like described in @{"Configfile" link Conf} !! Without one ADD won't work !!



@{u}ToolTypes@{uu}


After you're done creating a configfile you should check the tooltypes:

CX_POPUP           Values: YES/NO  Default: YES
                   Window popup on start

CX_POPKEY          Values: any keydescriptor  Default: lamiga d
                   Specifies the popup-key 

CX_PRIORITY        Values: Integer  Default: 0
                   Priority of AmiDynDNS commodity. You normaly mustn't
                   change this.

MINUTES            Values: 2-1440  Default: 30
                   Time interval between update attempts. Must be between 2
                   and 1440 minutes, all other values causes the default of 30
                   mins.

WEBIP              Values: YES/NO  Default: NO
                   Global de-/activation of web-based ip detection.

LOGGING            Values: YES/NO  Default: NO
                   De-/Activation of logging

LOGPATH            Values: any path  Default: S:
                   Specifies the save path for the logfile.

CONFPATH           Values: any path  Default: PROGDIR: or S:
                   Specifies the path of the configfile. If not specified it
                   will be searched for in PROGDIR: and S:

UPDATE_ONLY_ONCE   Values: YES/NO  Default: NO
                   If YES, AmiDynDNS will quit after the first successfull
                   update attempt.

UPDATE_IMMEDIATELY Values: YES/NO  Default: NO
                   If YES the first update attempt will be started immediately
                   after calling AmiDynDNS. Useful if it's sure the TCP/IP
                   stack is running and online and you don't want to wait.

SET_ENV_IP         Value: YES/NO  Default: NO
                   If YES AmiDynDNS will write the actual IP address in the
                   enviroment variable 'IP' (Env:IP). This might be useful if
                   the host is behind a router and you want to use i.e. RC-FTPd
                   in passive-mode.


Note: If you want to start AmiDynDNS from WBStartup drawer, you must
      add the system tooltype 'DONOTWAIT'.



@{u}Application-Window@{uu}


Configfile ok? Tooltypes ok? Then you can start AmiDynDNS with
double-click on its icon. A small window will appear which contains
a status line, a counter and three buttons (see figur below):

             .----------------------------------------.
			 |·|_AmiDynDNS v1.20__________________|o|o|
             |                                        |
             | .------------------------------------. |
             | |Status line                         | |
             | `------------------------------------' |
             |                    .-------.           |
             |        Time to go: |Counter|           |
             |                    `-------'           |
             | .----.         .------.         .----. |
             | |Quit|         |Update|         |Hide| |
             | `----'         `------'         `----' |
             `----------------------------------------'

In the status line AmiDynDNS shows you it status (oh, really? ;) ), what
its doing right now and/or the return value of the last update attempt.

The counter shows the seconds remaining before the next update attempt.

The buttons are self-explaining, aren't they? 'Quit' for quitting the
application, 'Update' for starting an update attempt of all hosts and
'Hide' for hiding the applications window.



@{u}Application-Menues@{uu}


Project
  |
  +------ About
  |       displays more or less usefull informations ;)
  |
  +------ Hide
  |       closes the window and sends AmiDynDNS in the background
  |
  +------ Quit
          quits AmiDynDNS


Actions
  |
  +------ Pause timer
  |       pauses/reactivates the timer (counter)
  |
  +------ Reset timer
  |       resets the counter value to initial value
  |
  +------ Update hosts
  |       starts an update attempt for all hosts (same like Update-
  |       Button)
  |
  +------ Be careful...
            |
            +------ Force update
                    AmiDynDNS will not update any host which ip is
                    already the same like your local one. If you want
                    to force an update, use pick this menuitem. But
                    use it careful, because DynDNS blocks hosts which
                    are too often updated!! I (the author) am not
                    responsible in any way for blocked hosts - you
                    have been warned!



@{u}Commodity behavior@{uu}


Since AmiDynDNS is a commodity you can affect it like any other
commodity via Exchange (or any other commodity controlling program).
You can open or close the window, pause, reactivate and quit AmiDynDNS.

If you want to learn more about commodities please refer to the
Workbench manual delivered with your AmigaOS.

@endnode


@node Conf "Configfile"
@next "Tags"
@prev "UsWB"

 @{b}@{u}Configfile@{ub}@{uu}

@{i}Note: For pure @{b}CLI use@{ub}, the configfile is fully @{b}optional@{ub},
      you can use AmiDynDNS without this file without any problems.

      For @{b}WB/Commodity use@{ub}, a proper configfile is absolutely @{b}necessary@{ub}!

      Anyway, with a suitable configfile life will be much easier ;-)@{ui}


The configfile must be located either in the AmiDynDNS PROGDIR:, in S: or in
the directory you specified with the CLI-argument/tooltype @{i}CONFIGFILE@{ui} called
'@{b}AmiDynDNS.cfg@{ub}'. The filename is @{i}case insensitive@{ui}!

Use your favorite ascii editor (e.g. Ed, CygnusED, GoldEd,..) and
open a new file (or edit the included sample config). Empty lines
or lines starting with '#' or withspace ' ' will be ignored. The
file consists of one or more account blocks limited in the beginnig
by <account> and in the end by </account>. Each block describes one
account with one or more hosts and options.

A @{b}minimum@{ub} block consists of

<BEGIN_TAG>
USER_TAG
PASSWORD_TAG
HOST_TAG
</END_TAG>


e.g.:

<account>
USER=john
PASS=doe
HOST=johndoe.dyndns.org
</account>

As you can see the beginning and end tags limit the block.
The information tags (USER, PASS, HOST, ...) must be followed
by one equal sign '=' and the appropriate information. All
tags and the information (including beginning and end tag)
are @{i}case insensitive@{ui}. Which means 'USER' is the same
as 'uSeR' or 'user'...

But note that the values of USER and PASS are @{i}case sensitive@{ui}!

Please note that the <account>, </account>, User, Pass and
Host tags are @{u}required@{uu} in any block. Additional Host tags or
tags for options are @{u}optional@{uu} and some may be even overwritten
by command-line arguments!
Also note that given options in one block affect @{b}all@{ub} hosts in
block!


See @{"Configtags" link Tags} for a complete list of possible
information tags.


A little bit more sophisticated example:

Imagine, you want to update host 'foo.dyndns.org' of your account
'ben' with password 'benspass' and the hosts 'bar.dyndns.org' and
'fubar.dnsalias.net' of your second account 'john' with password
'johnspass' and one MaileXchanger host 'mail.john.org' for both
of johns's hosts you would create a configfile like this:


-------------------snip----------------
#
# Sample configfile for AmiDynDNS
#

<account>
user=ben
pass=benspass
host=foo.dyndns.org
</account>

<Account>
User=john
Pass=johnspass
Host=bar.dyndns.org
Host=fubar.dnsalias.net
Mx=mail.john.org
</Account>

-------------------snip----------------


A sample configfile is part of this distribution. Take a look at
it, modify it, use it :-)
@endnode

@node Tags "Tags in the Configfile"
@next "Hist"
@prev "Conf"

 @{b}@{u}Tags in the Configfile@{ub}@{uu}

As mentioned in @{"Configfile" link Conf} AmiDynDNS uses a new structure for
the configfile. The allowed and possible tags are described in this
section. For better description what the individual options do, please
refer to the argument description in @{"Usage" link Usag}.


Except the beginning and end tags all other tags must be followed by
one euqal sign '=' and the information! See the sample config included
in this archive.


@{u}Always required tags:@{uu}

<account>      Marks the beginning of a new account block.

</account>     Marks the end of an account block.

USER           Followed by your DynDNS username.

PASS           Followed by your DynDNS password.

HOST           Followed by your DynDNS host your wisch to update.
               This tag can be specified multiple times in one block
               (for updating two or more hosts of one users with the
               same options).


@{u}Optional tags:@{uu}

Note that optional tags which are specified in one block affect *all*
hosts of that block! If you want two hosts with *different* options you
must specify two *different* blocks!

SYSTEM         Followed by the DynDNS system used for the hosts in that
               block. DYNDNS, STATDNS or CUSTOM. Default is DYNDNS.

WILD           Followed by 'YES' activates the wildcard option of each
               given host in that block.

MX             Followed by a full qualified domain name or valid IP
               sets the Mail eXchanger to the given one.

BACKMX         Followed by 'YES' sets the given MX up as a backup.


Sample configs are listed in @{"Configfile" link Conf} or in the
included sample AmiDynDNS.cfg.
@endnode

@node Hist "History of AmiDynDNS"
@next "Futu"
@prev "Tags"

 @{b}@{u}History of AmiDynDNS@{ub}@{uu}


@{b}v1.20@{ub} (24.11.2005)  @{i}*Probably FINAL public release*@{ui}

	(Bin zu faul das jetzt zu übersetzen.. ;) )

	OMG.. long time no see! Almost 2 years since the last update and
	this one could just be made because i stumbled uppon the updated
	source by accident :-)
	Well, nothing special this time, besides the latest version is
	finally on Aminet.. Aminet rulez!

	- Direct support for SMC routers removed!
	  There are way to much different routers with different mechanism
	  to support out there, so i decided to ditch this rather pointless
	  support. Besides, most users will probably already use some router
	  with direct DynDNS support build in.
	- Fixed email and http strings all over the place
	- Updated version information
	- Revised documentation
	- Fixed some minor other bugs..IIRC.. I forgot what exactly i fixed.
	  Yet another example how highly important changenotes are :-/

@{b}v1.19@{ub} (04.12.2003)  @{i}*PUBLIC RELEASE*@{ui}

    - Web based IP detection works again. This error caused the up2date
      check of hosts to fail and to get some of these hosts blocked.
    - EMail, snailmail and WWW addresses updated.
    - Now the logfile gets also entries for skipped (because up2date)
      hosts.
    - Tooltype MINUTES now accepts values between 2 and 1440 minutes
      (1440 minutes == 24 hours)
    - Default of update interval changed to 30 minutes.
    - Timer now shows remaining time as HH:MM:SS.
    - If ADD is paused the status line now shows "Paused..." and
      if its resumed again the status shows "Ready...".

@{b}v1.18@{ub} (30.10.2003)

    - Rarely happened error in the authentification fixed.
    - Internal IP detection for OS4 modified.

@{b}v1.17@{ub} (11.03.2003)  @{i}*PUBLIC RELEASE*@{ui}

    - New CLI argument SETENVIP/S
    - New tooltype SET_ENV_IP
    - CLI output fixed
    - minor bugs in log routine fixed
    - ported to Vbcc

@{b}v1.16@{ub} (13.12.2002)  @{i}*PUBLIC RELEASE*@{ui}

    - "CX_POPUP=NO"-Bug fixed
    - minor optimizations

@{b}v1.15@{ub} (02.09.2002)  @{i}*PUBLIC RELEASE*@{ui}

    - gui is now font sensitive
    - new tooltype added (UPDATE_IMMEDIATELY=[YES|NO])
    - small gui bug fixed

@{b}v1.1@{ub} (13.08.2002)  @{i}*PUBLIC RELEASE*@{ui}

    - done ;))
    - graphical prefs cancelled and all prefs-code removed
      sorry, but it makes no sense IMO..
    - minor optimizations and bugfixes
      you can't imagine how much small but f*cking bugs could
      reside in a small piece of code like this... grrr
    - prepared for new DynDNS client interface
    - guide/docs updated

@{b}v1.0b2@{ub} (20.06.2002)

    - timer routines changed for less cpu load :P
    - some minor bugfixes

@{b}v1.0b1@{ub} (01.04.2002)  @{i}*PUPLIC BETA RELEASE*@{ui}

    - commodity support added (CLI/WB hybrid)
    - small 'easy2use' GUI added
    - various tooltypes added
    - LOGPATH/K and CONFPATH/K for cli part added

@{b}v0.91@{ub} (03.03.2002)  @{i}*PUBLIC RELEASE*@{ui}

    - USER and PASS values in configfile are now case sensitive!
    - german translation of the guide added (Scooby)
    - documentation updated

@{b}v0.9@{ub} (29.02.2002)  @{i}*PUBLIC RELEASE*@{ui}

    - Yiiiiihaaa..!! ;-)
    - bugs fixed, no crashes anymore (i hope)
    - many new features added: STATDNS, CUSTOMDNS, SMC SUPPORT,
      SMCIP OVERRIDE, MX, BACKMX, WILDCARD, LOCAL-IP-CHECK,
      HOST-UP2DATE-CHECK, PROXY, FORCE
    - configuration file structure changed
    - official Remedy Systems tool ;)
    - Freeware again.

@{b}v0.83 - v0.891@{ub}

    - some f*cking hard days of work coz some really nasty
      bugs caused total freezing and crashes ;((
      I'm sorry about that.

@{b}v0.82@{ub} (18.02.2002)  @{i}*PUBLIC RELEASE*@{ui}

    - little bug in logfile routines fixed

@{b}v0.81@{ub} (18.02.2002)

    - web-based IP detection added,
      useful behind gateways or routers..
    - little help option added.
    - minor bug in http-header fixed.
    - documentation updated (i wont write this down to the history
      in the future, coz it's clear, isn't it? ;) )

@{b}v0.8@{ub} (10.02.2002) @{i}*PUBLIC RELEASE*@{ui}

    - config file routines completed,
      now you can update one or more hosts of one or more users at
      once without a large cli line
    - internal code structure changed (better performance)
    - AmigaGuide documentation completed, bye bye big readme :)

@{b}v0.72@{ub} (08.02.2002)

    - some code optimizations, now AmiDynDNS needs a little bit more
      than 2KB stack ;)
    - OFFLINE switch added (only for donators usefull!)
    - Config file parser added (one account per line),
      well, it works... somehow... it's in pre-alpha stage as it
      were.. lots of work has to be done before next public release :-/
    - documentation updated

@{b}v0.71@{ub} (08.02.2002)

After a lot of damn tests at university, i've finally found some time
to spend on coding...;-)

    - parsing routines fixed to get clear messages from DynDNS
      HTML body (reply), coz the mates of DynDNS changed the
      format, but forgot telling us this 'little' behavior in their
      developer mailinglist ;( WHY HAVE I JOINED THE LIST? !&#%/
    - minor bug in log file routines fixed
    - log file routines revised,
      now it checks for filesize *and* date to avoid splitting log
      entries of one day in .log and .bak file

@{b}v0.7@{ub}  (25.01.2002) @{i}*PUBLIC RELEASE*@{ui}

    - optional log file implemented
    - log-size-limit (4KB) and backup implemented
    - nasty overflow bug FIXED
    - documentation updated

@{b}v0.64@{ub} (24.01.2002)

    - QUIET option implemented
    - documentation updated

@{b}v0.63@{ub} (19.01.2002) @{i}*FIRST PUBLIC RELEASE*@{ui}

    - determination method for own IP changed for better
      compatibility
    - documentation created

@{b}v0.62@{ub} (18.01.2002)

    - little changes on connection routines added

@{b}v0.61@{ub} (18.01.2002)

    - some little corrections in response parser for better
      performance
 
@{b}v0.6@{ub}  (18.01.2002)

    - complete server response handling implemented
    - standard output and progress output routines expanded
    - all seems to be ok, almost finished for release? :)

@{b}v0.5@{ub}  (18.01.2002)

    - some utility functions revised
    - error handling updated & revised
    - http read function changed for better transparency

@{b}v0.41@{ub} (17.01.2002)

    - Silly mistake in HTTP-Request fixed

@{b}v0.4@{ub}  (17.01.2002)

    - final HTTP-Request with respect to options for
      DynDNS NIC-2 implemented
    - output functions for usage and basic errors inserted

@{b}v0.3@{ub}  (17.01.2002)

    - base64 encryption routine corrected & revised
    - some additional option-checks implemented

@{b}v0.2@{ub}  (16.01.2002)

    - CLI-Options in Amiga style (RDargs) implemented
    - Some helpful functions were coded
    - base64 encryption implemented

@{b}v0.1@{ub}  (16.01.2002)

    - First basically 'running' version ;)
      Does only some basic stuff like socket,
      connection, sends some HTTP stuff and
      receives the response
@endnode
